##### UNIVERSAL OPTIONS ####

### U_AINUV2: AINULINDALE V2
#
#   AINULINDALE V2 integrates directly into android's native audio
#   pipeline at the primitives layer, replacing key processing
#   stages with custom implementations. Every stage is designed for
#   deterministic low-latency execution, combining thread-local
#   architecture, lock-free processing and SIMD acceleration to
#   preserve the signal with exceptional transparency and fidelity:
#
#   Custom Bessel > custom Kaiser window coefficient generation
#   by James34602 > machine-precision convergence
#                 > minimizes numerical error during resampling
#
#   DC Blocker    > removes DC offset in real time
#                 > preserves sub-bass phase response
#                 > protects downstream DSP from offset buildup
#
#   TPDF Dither   > mathematically correct triangular dithering
#                 > 2nd-order noise-shaped quantization
#                 > transparent bit-depth reduction
#
#   Deferred Gain > preserves full internal signal precision
#                 > applies attenuation only at final output
#                 > maintains low-level DR at any volume
#
#   Soft Limiter  > true-peak aware oversampled protection
#                 > transparent below threshold
#                 > smooth analog-inspired saturation on overload
#
# 	             Might not work on some devices.
# !          CAN RESULT IN BUGS/SOUND LOSS/BOOTLOOP               !
#   SILMARIL performs the check during installation and will
#   print a warning in case there are any potential issues
#
#   You can set *U_AINUV2=true* to use AINULINDALE V2 engine
#
U_AINUV2=

### U_HL: SAMPLER HALF LENGTH
#
#   Variable resampling rate sampler is practically linear
#   phase with a symmetrical impulse response that ensures
#   the phase shift is proportional to the frequency. Half
#   Length is the number of samples till IR center.
#
#   A shorter IR (smaller half length) allows for a faster
#   transition between frequencies, resulting in a steeper
#   filter response and potentially higher aliasing.
#
#   A longer impulse response (larger half length) allows
#   for a more gradual transition and improves frequency
#   selectivity. Additionally, a longer IR facilitates
#   better attenuation of aliasing components, reducing
#   unwanted artifacts in the signal. However, this comes
#   at the cost of potentially higher latency.
#
#   Filter length = steepness = halflength*2
#
#   SILMARIL sets *960* taps polyphase filter, which can
#   be considered as studio master quality.
#
# !       *960* taps might be too high for some devices          !
# !        Leading to various sound issues & artifacts           !
# !    If that's your case - set *U_HL* to *480* taps or less    !
#
U_HL=960

### U_SBA: SAMPLER STOPBAND ATTENUATION
#
#   Sampling always alias - high frequency signals can fold
#   back onto lower frequencies creating distortions. To
#   mitigate that stopband attenuation is used. It can also
#   slightly reduce noise interference and suppress aliasing
#   from frequencies above the Nyquist limit.
#
#   By default, the maximum stopband value is limited to
#   144dB (24bit). This remains relevant for most commonly
#   used audio formats.
#
#   You can experiment setting *U_SBA* per format, however,
#   since the output is always constrained by hardware's
#   noise floor - best way is setting *U_SBA* value around
#   device's SNR.
#
#   SILMARIL sets stopband attenuation to *127*, which is
#   around the practical reach for most devices.
#
U_SBA=127

##
### U_VSTP: VOLUME SLIDER STEPS
#
#   OS volume is calculated from a logarithmic attenuation
#   curve, where a volume index maps corresponding dB value.
#   Db is then converted to an amplitude scale. OS fills gaps
#   between the index points linearly.
#   Perfectly, *U_VSTP* value should reflect the entire index
#   range (*100*) allowed by OS. This way slider steps match
#   points index, allowing for granular volume adjustment without
#   any linear rounding inbetween steps.
#
# 	*Ex: U_VSTP=100* for recommended volume steps/amplitude slider.
#
U_VSTP=

### U_VCRE: VOLUME CURVE REATTENUATION
#
#   The volume curve determines how loudness scales to the 
#   volume slider steps.
#   Since human hearing and different audio gear perceive
#   sound levels differently, changing this curve alters
#   how responsive, sensitive, or smooth individual volume
#   steps feel across the slider range.
#
#   You can choose between:
#   Logarithmic > smooth control at higher volumes
#               > stretches out the lower decibel steps
#               > can feel "dead" or very quiet below 50%
#               > default fallback / traditional scaling
#
#   Linear      > equal decibel steps across the entire scale
#               > highly predictable and uniform progression
#               > very smooth transition in the upper half
#               > can take a moment to wake up from total zero
#
#   Cubic       > snappy and responsive low-end control
#               > rapidly climbs out of initial digital silence
#               > expands the usable moderate listening range
#               > ideal for high-sensitivity headphones or IEMs
#
#   SILMARIL will automatically reattenuate the curve based off 
#   desired *U_VSTP* value. If no *U_VSTP* is set, the standard
#   aosp value is used.
#
#   Possible *U_VCRE* values: *log lin cub*
# 	*Ex: U_VSTP=log* for logarithmic curve
#
U_VCRE=
##

### U_ESTV: EQUAL STEREO SPEAKER VOLUME 
#
#   Devices that use earpiece in stereo mode sometimes
#   set unequal curves for both speakers. This creates
#   perceivable inconsistency between the two. 
#   SILMARIL can set a custom well attenuated curve for
#   both speakers to mitigate that issue for media playback
#   scenarios.
#   Keep in mind that earpiece is usually different from
#   the main speaker - so even if equal curve is set for
#   both, you still might experience inconsistent output.
#
#   You can set *U_ESTV=true* to force use equal vol, or
#   leave untouched for default behavior
#
U_ESTV=

### U_APFF: FLOATING POINT FORMAT
#
#   Usually, even being present in the system - floating
#   point format *AUDIO_FORMAT_PCM_FLOAT* isn't exposed
#   in audio policy interface. *U_APFF* lets you add, or
#   force float format to attached mix and device ports.
#
#   You can choose between:
#   Add (default): float format is added to ports along the
#        full list of all system-supported formats.
#
#   Force: existing format profiles are commented out and
#          ports are forced to float format only.
#
#   Chances of any app calling for float format playback
#   are extremely slim, but in case of such scenario -
#   adding it to the list of exposed formats is a good
#   idea. For example, some audio formats, like flac can
#   be decoded by system (non-offload) as float.
#
#   When forced - system will have to convert source to
#   float and in some cases back (unless decoding as float).
#   This doesn't seem to bring any benefits rightaway.
#   However, when dealing with float - parts of native
#   audio subsystem are branched to a more precise math
#   as well. This is somewhat benefitial for AINULINDALE.
#   The most interesting case is the volume power calc -
#   floating point provides higher range numbers compared
#   to that of integer formats. This results in android
#   giving float a head of *+3dBFS* above the max threshold
#   - in other words, it's *~41%* more amplitude before
#   sound starts clipping and distorting.
#   Note that most SOC internal codecs are unlikely to
#   support float format, neither do some external dacs
#   - which would result in yet another conversion.
#
#   Feel free to experiment.
#   By default SILMARIL uses *add* to expose all system-
#   supported formats in attached ports.
#
#   You can set *U_APFF=add* to add float format, or
#   *U_APFF=force* to force float format only.
#
U_APFF=

### U_APDBR: DEEP BUFFER REMOVAL
#
#   A common misconception throughout all these years being
#   deepbuffer somehow responsible for worsening audio.
#   If the idea being deepbuffer is bad for setting low
#   power state, then in reality it's the opposite of bad.
#   When audio is processed it's chopped into chunks - i.e.
#   frames. The higher the fidelity of the source - the
#   more frames. These frames have to be buffered correctly
#   to avoid any underruns, which is the reason for deepbuffer
#   to exist. It provides enough memory for all chunks without
#   any need for constant processing them on the go. When
#   deepbuffer is removed - the system is likely to fallback
#   to either of ll threads. Which might result in buffer underrun,
#   and definitely in wasted processing/battery resources.
#
#   By default SILMARIL adds system-supported profiles to
#   deepbuffer to mitigate the intention of dbuffer removal
#   due to lack of exposed formats (for external app to form
#   a playbackthread).
#   But if for whatever reason removing deepbuffer is absolutely
#   vital - you can do so by setting *U_APDBR=true*, this 
#   will eliminate as many deepbuffer tails in the system
#   as possible.
#
U_APDBR=

